{
  "texts": [
    "For each of the included studies, there is not one single effect size, but a so-called vector of effect sizes (i.e., a one-column matrix of effect sizes) is created and used in the analyses.",
    "When multiple effect sizes are extracted from primary studies, they can differ in strength (and even in direction) across studies, but also within studies.",
    "The multivariate model takes both this between-study",
    "The Quantitative Methods for Psychology 2 and within-study variability in effect sizes into account.",
    "The within-study variability is captured by the sampling variance-covariance matrix that is assumed to be known and encompasses the individual variance of each effect size as well as the relations (covariances) between the sampling errors of effect sizes within an individual study."
  ]
}